<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-s03e01">
    <title>Episode 1: What Fractions Represent</title>
    <assemblage>
        <title>Episode 1 Learning Goals</title>
        <p>
           <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                  Determine the physical quantity represented by a fraction.  
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                   Interpret fractions on physical objects such as measuring tapes and measuring cups.  
                </p>
            </li>
           </ul> 
        </p>
    </assemblage>
    <assemblage>
        <title>Episode 1 Key Terminology</title>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Fraction
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Numerator
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Denominator
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </assemblage>

    <definition xml:id="def-fraction">
        <statement>
            <p>
                A <term>fraction</term> A fraction represents a portion of a whole.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      Fractions are related to division. The fraction <m>\frac{1}{4}</m> also written as 1/4, would correspond to dividing 1 object into 4 portions: 
      <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                You would have to start by cutting the object into 4 equally sized pieces.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Then each portion would consist of 1 of those pieces. 
            </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
    <sidebyside>
        <figure>
            <caption>1/4 of a round pizza</caption>
        <image>
            <shortdescription>1/4 of a round pizza</shortdescription>
            <prefigure>
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                <coordiantes bbox= "(-5,-5,5,5)">
                <axes decorations="no">
                    <circle center="(0,0)" radius="4.5" stroke="grey" thickness="2"/>
                    <arc center="(0,0)" radius="4.5" stroke="orange" thickness="5" range="(-3*pi/2,0)"/>
                    <arc center="(0,0)" radius="4.25" stroke="red" thickness="5" range="(-3*pi/2,0)"/>
                    <arc center="(0,0)" radius="4.0"  sector="yes" fill="yellow" range="(-3*pi/2,0)"/>
                </axes>
                </coordinates>
                </diagram>
             </prefigure>   
        </image>
        </figure>
        <figure>
            <caption>1/4 of a square</caption>
        <image>
            <shortdescription>1/4 of square</shortdescription>
            <prefigure>
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                <coordiantes bbox= "(-5,-5,5,5)">
                <axes decorations="no" stroke="grey">
                    <rectangle center="(0,0)" dimensions="(10,10)" stroke="grey" thickness="2"/>
                    <rectangle center="(-2.5,2.5)" dimensions="(5,5)" fill="grey">
                </axes>
                </coordinates>
                </diagram>
             </prefigure>   
        </image>
        </figure>
    </sidebyside>

    
</section>